1

00:00:02,589  -->  00:00:07,655
You're now been introduced to a few different applications for confidence intervals,

2

00:00:07,655  -->  00:00:11,855
as well as a bootstrapping approach to creating these confidence intervals.

3

00:00:11,855  -->  00:00:16,024
We found that creating a confidence interval for the differences in means of two groups,

4

00:00:16,024  -->  00:00:18,934
rather than just comparing two point value estimates,

5

00:00:18,934  -->  00:00:22,129
is important to assure that the differences are not just

6

00:00:22,129  -->  00:00:26,184
occurring due to the randomness associated with the sample that was chosen.

7

00:00:26,184  -->  00:00:29,535
Confidence intervals are certainly useful.

8

00:00:29,535  -->  00:00:31,410
But there are issues that can arise when

9

00:00:31,410  -->  00:00:35,390
exclusively using confidence intervals to make decisions.

10

00:00:35,390  -->  00:00:41,009
This brings up the ideas of Practical and Statistical Significance.

11

00:00:41,009  -->  00:00:45,729
Let's consider an example to illustrate the difference between these two terms.

12

00:00:45,729  -->  00:00:50,049
Imagine that I own a dog walking business and I'm advertising online.

13

00:00:50,049  -->  00:00:52,409
I would like to know which of these two ads would

14

00:00:52,409  -->  00:00:55,629
help me generate the most interest in my business.

15

00:00:55,630  -->  00:00:58,200
I send out each ad to the same number of

16

00:00:58,200  -->  00:01:01,650
randomly selected users and I build the confidence interval,

17

00:01:01,649  -->  00:01:04,664
that suggests that more people click this ad.

18

00:01:04,665  -->  00:01:06,789
Based on my confidence interval,

19

00:01:06,789  -->  00:01:11,700
I have statistical evidence to suggest that the second ad is better.

20

00:01:11,700  -->  00:01:17,700
This evidence we get from the confidence interval is just this, Statistical Significance.

21

00:01:17,700  -->  00:01:19,814
Let's say that both ads generate

22

00:01:19,814  -->  00:01:23,804
enough interest to achieve more dogs than I can even handle watching.

23

00:01:23,805  -->  00:01:29,470
And that the second ad is much more expensive and time-consuming to create.

24

00:01:29,469  -->  00:01:32,039
If a friend of yours decides that they would like to build

25

00:01:32,040  -->  00:01:35,910
a similar ad campaign to start their own dog walking business,

26

00:01:35,909  -->  00:01:38,549
which type of ad would you recommend to them?

27

00:01:38,549  -->  00:01:41,920
In this case, you might suggest something like the first ad,

28

00:01:41,920  -->  00:01:45,695
even though you statistically prove that the second ad was better.

29

00:01:45,694  -->  00:01:48,929
The first ad will generate enough interest in

30

00:01:48,930  -->  00:01:52,705
their business and be less expensive and time intensive.

31

00:01:52,704  -->  00:01:58,950
Your suggestion for them to use the first ad is an example of Practical Significance.

32

00:01:58,950  -->  00:02:00,990
Practical significance takes into

33

00:02:00,989  -->  00:02:04,004
consideration additional aspects and the world around us,

34

00:02:04,004  -->  00:02:05,819
rather than just the numbers.

35

00:02:05,819  -->  00:02:08,310
And it's critically important to making your decisions.
